What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset consists of 18207 rows and 89 columns. Some columns have missing values. Column 28 to 53 which consist of player position information have missing values. Columns Release Clause, Joined, Loaned From and Contract Valid Until also have a substantial amount of missing values.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My interest is to show relationships between different characteristics and stats of the players and also to show how the most valuable players rank against each other.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

A number of characteristics available in the dataset will be useful in my investigation. Some of them including BallControl, Strength, Agility, Age, Balance, Stamina etc. The dataset is large so it will be fun exploring all these variables.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I explored individual variables in the dataset and their distribution. Some of the questions I asked myself were:

  1. Which country do most players come from? To answer This question, I used the variable Nationality.
  2. What age are most players in the game and what is the average age of players? Variable in use was Age.
  3. Which is the most preferred foot foot by most players? Variable in use was Preferred Foot
  4. Which overall rating did most players fall in?
  5. Which positions had the most players?

From the above plots, we gather that most players' preferred foot is their right foot with some players having the left foot as their preferred foot for playing. We also see that a high number of players in the game fall under an overall rating of 66 with most players distributed between ratings of 60 and 72. We also learn that a high number of players in the game play striker(ST) positions followed by goalkeepers (GK) then center back (CB) positions.

In [17]:
#plotting Skill Moves and Dribbling
def plot_1():
    """Plot the variables Skill Moves and Dribbling."""
    df = pd.read_csv('data.csv')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, figsize = [9,8])
    variables = ['Skill Moves', 'Dribbling']
    for i in range(len(variables)):
        var = variables[i]
        bins = np.arange(min(df[var]), max(df[var])+0.2, 0.2)
        ax[i].hist(data = df, x = var, bins = bins)
        ax[i].set_xlabel('{}'.format(var))

    plt.show()

The above plot shows the distribution on Player Dribbling ability and Skill moves. We see that most players fall between 50 and 80 in Dribbling and between 2.0 and 3.3 in Skill Moves.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of the variables in my investigation was different for different variables. Most seemed regular with few to null unusual points. No data transformation was required before my analysis as the data available was clean.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There were no unusual distributions in te features i investigated. The variables I used for my investigation did not require any tidying or adjustment.

#Plotting a correlation heat map
numeric_variables = ['Overall','Reactions','Balance','ShotPower','Jumping','Stamina','Strength','LongShots','Aggression','Interceptions','Positioning','Vision','Penalties','Composure','Marking','StandingTackle','SlidingTackle']
plt.figure(figsize = [20, 20])
sb.heatmap(df[numeric_variables].corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0)
plt.show()

Due to the number of variables not being able to fit in one chart and be visible, I divided the data into two charts for easy assessment and better visibility. As we know, there is stronger correlation between two variables when the correlation coefficient is closer to 1 or -1 and weaker as it goes to 0. Frome above chart, we see a strong correlation between a number of attributes/variable. For example:

Sliding Tackle, Standing Tackle and Marking have a strong correlation with interceptions. Sliding Tackle and Standing Tackle have a strong correlation. We also see a strong correlation between ShotPower and LongShot, Penalties and LongShots, Positioning and LongShots, Reactions and Overall, Penalties and Positioning. We see no variables with a strong negative correlation.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

From the above plots in the grid, we gather some insights on the different positions and their abilities. Here are some of the insights I gathered:

  1. We see the players in Right Forward (RF) position having strong Dribbling Skills and Shot power regardless of foot being used. However, not many players playing this position.
  2. A number of players play striker (ST) position with their distribution varying but most being above average in Shot power and Dribbling.
  3. Players playing Left Wing (LW) position were also above average in dribbling and shot power however there is on outlier in the shot power plot.
  4. We see goalkeepers (GK) having weak dribbling and shot power capabilities which makes sense since their role does not require much skilset in the two,
  5. Right Center Mid (RCM) position players have an above average ability in the two abilities.
  6. Left Forward position (LF) players are few according to the distribution in the plot and above average in dribbling and shot power.
  7. Right Strikers (RS) were also above average in both dribbling and shot power except a few outliers.
  8. All players playing Center Back(CB) position had a rating of less than 70 in both dribbling and shot power.
  9. Center Attacking Midfield (CAM) players had a similar distribution for both Left Foot and Right Foot players.
  10. Most players playing Center Defensive Midfield are rightfooted.
  11. Most Right Strikers(RS) have an above average Shot Power and are right footed.
  12. Few players play Left Attacking Midfield (LAM) position.
  13. A large number of players playing Left Back (LB) and Left Wing Back (LWB) position have their prefereed foot as the left.
  14. Right Defensive Midfield(RDM), Right Back(RB) and Right Wing(RW) players mostly preferred their right foot.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

There was a clear correlation between Preferred foot and the position the player plays.

Conclusions¶

After Exploratory Analysis of the dataset, I have come across a number of insights most of which I've listed below their respective plots. We see clear correlation between attributes of the players that seem to complement each other.
